Japan, India, Korea, Thailand, Indonesia: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   A n i l   V a r m a
-- 
2011-05-30T22:12:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/japan-india-korea-thailand-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The  Finance Ministry  will announce at 10:30 a.m. the amount
of 30-year  government bonds  it plans to sell on June 7.  The statistics bureau will publish at 8:30 a.m. its report
on overall household spending and jobless rate for April. The
 unemployment rate  rose to 4.7 percent from 4.6 percent in March,
according to the median estimate of economists before the
statistics bureau reports the data at 8:30 a.m.  The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare will publish at
8:30 a.m. its report on the job-to-applicants ratio for April.
 Japan ’s job-to-applicants ratio slid to 0.62 from 0.63 in the
previous month, another survey showed.  The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. a preliminary
report on industrial production for April. Factory output grew 2
percent from March, when it plunged 15.5 percent, according to
economists surveyed by Bloomberg News.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.12 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 80.95 per dollar at 7:03 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : The central bank will sell 3 billion yuan ($463
million) of one-year notes today.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.83
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.4829.  India : Asia’s third-largest economy expanded 8.1 percent in
the first quarter from a year earlier, following an 8.2 percent
gain in the previous three months, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey before data
due today.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.46
percent. The rupee was at 45.0725.  Indonesia: The government will offer Islamic debt maturing
in five, 10 and 15 years.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 7.38
percent. The rupiah was at 8,548.  South Korea: A government report today will show industrial
production increased 9.2 percent in April from a year earlier,
following an 8.7 percent gain the previous month, according to a
Bloomberg News survey of economists.  The yield on  South Korea ’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.58 percent. The won was at 1,080.10 per dollar.  Thailand: The nation posted a deficit of $700 million in
April, compared with a surplus of $1.9 billion in March,
according to the median estimate of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg ahead of data due today.  The central bank plans to raise a combined 58 billion baht
($1.9 billion) selling 28-, 91- and 182-day bills.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.46 percent. The baht was at 30.34 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anil Varma in Mumbai at 
